 }{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 provides Knowledge Base (KB) articles on known issues.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Also, the latest version of the }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 SDK (which includes support for the Palm-size PC devices) contains a complete Blackjack Sample application that can\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  be used as a template.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.  CAB Wizard (CabWiz)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ----------------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.1.\tab What does CabWiz do?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 CabWiz is the desktop SDK tool that packages your application binaries into a single }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 CAB file.  It uses a CabWiz INF file, \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
which contains setup commands such as where to copy device files, and what device registry settings to make.  With the CabWiz INF file and your application binaries, it will create multiple platform-specific }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB files, which is used to \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 install your application to a }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{
\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  device.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.2.\tab What is a CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A CabWiz INF file is a modified version of the Win32 INF file format.  The Win32 INF file format is a documented Win32 format used to describe setup commands, such\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 as copying files and creating registry settings.  The CabWiz INF file format uses the Win32 INF file format, with various INF commands added and removed.  A single CabWiz INF file is used by CabWiz to create a CAB file for each targeted platform (such as
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 the H/PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , }{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Palm-size PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , or Pocket PC, etc.
}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ).
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.3.\tab What is a }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB file?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB file is a Win32 CAB file containing }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{
\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 -specific files.  The Win32 CAB file is the Microsoft file format use\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d for compressing and distributing multiple files.  The }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB file uses the Win32 CAB file format to store the setup information (the CabWiz INF file) plus your device-side application binaries.  A single CAB file contains device-specific
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  binaries for a targeted platform (such as the H/PC on a MIPS CPU, or a Palm-size PC on an SH3 CPU}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , or a Pocket PC, etc.}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
).  This means that CabWiz can be used to create a number of CAB files, each CAB file for a specific device type.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.4.\tab How do I call C\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 abWiz?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Running CabWiz without any parameters will provide a usage message box.  The important thing to note is to call CabWiz with a double-quoted absolute path to the CabWiz INF file.  Also, to have CabWiz create multiple CAB files for supporting multipl
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e device types, you will need to use the "/cpu" flag followed by a set of Platform Labels (described in a later section).
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.5.\tab Can CabWiz INF files be used for installing on Win9x}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , }{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 WinNT}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
, or WinXP}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 No.  CabWiz INF files are only specific to }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , and cannot be used for installing on Win9x}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , }{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 WinNT}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , or WinXP}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 machines.  Also, Win32 INF files (created for Win9x or WinNT) cannot be used on }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
.  However, you can use a Win32 INF file as a template - a CabWiz INF fi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 le is a Win32 INF file with various INF commands added and removed.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.6.\tab What other support files are used by CabWiz?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 CabWiz is installed with 2 other support files: MakeCab.exe and CabWiz.ddf.  Both these files must be in the same directory as CabWiz.e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 xe.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.7.\tab Can I create a }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB file using "makecab.exe"?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 No.  MakeCab.exe is the actual program that will create CAB files - however, it will not incorporate the setup information provided in your CabWiz INF file.  CabWiz.exe is the pro\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
gram to use to create }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB files.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.8.\tab What are Directory IDs, and how do I use them?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 CabWiz INF Directory IDs are identifiers used to specify standard device directories in the CabWiz INF file, such as "\\Windows" and "\\Windows\\Start \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Menu".  The format of a Directory ID is %CEx%, where "x" is a number.  These Directory IDs will be replaced with the full path at device application installation runtime.  The list of all supported CabWiz INF Directory IDs for H/PCs and Palm-size PCs are 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ocumented in the }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  SDK.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.9.\tab What are Platform Labels, and how do I use them?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Platform Labels are used to make CabWiz create multiple platform-specific CAB files from a single CabWiz INF file.  The Platform Labels tells CabWiz how many\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 CAB files to generate, where to get the CPU-specific binary files, and the platform information to incorporate into the CAB file, so that for example, the end-user will not be able to install an H/PC SH3 processor CAB file on to a Palm-size PC MIPS proce
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 sor device.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Platform Labels are unique labels that are appended to specific sections in the CabWiz INF file (see the }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 SDK docs).  The main section that differentiates the platforms is the [CEDevice] INF section, which allows for device-\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 specific information, such as the processor type, the device types (H/PC or Palm-size PC) supported, the }{
\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  OS version supported, etc.  These Platform Labels also need to be specified in the command-line parameters when invoking CabWiz.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  full example of using Platform Labels is found in the Blackjack Sample application included with the latest version of the }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{
\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  SDK (which includes support for the Palm-size PC devices).
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.10.\tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 How do I use a literal % (percent) symbol in the CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Use %% in the CabWiz INF file to represent a single literal % symbol.  However, this cannot be used under the [Strings] section, since every string under the [Strings] section needs to be e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nclosed by % symbols to perform string substitutions.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.11.\tab How do I use a literal double-quote (") symbol in the CabWiz INF file?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Use "" in the CabWiz INF file to represent a literal double-quote (").
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.12.\tab Things to check for when encountering error\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s with CabWiz
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - The }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 SDK-included files "MakeCab.exe" and "CabWiz.ddf" must be in the same directory as "CabWiz.exe"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Call "CabWiz.exe" with double-quoted absolute path
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Use a double-quoted absolute path for the CabWiz INF file parameter
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Verify in the INF file that string lists do not have trailing commas or unnecessary/extra spaces - example:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Invalid:\tab CopyFiles=Files.Common,  Files.Cpu,
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Valid:\tab CopyFiles=Files.Common\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ,Files.Cpu
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.  Application Manager (AppMgr)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 -----------------------------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.1.\tab What does AppMgr do?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 AppMgr is the desktop tool installed by ActiveSync that provides desktop-to-devic\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e application management, similar to Windows Add/Remove Programs.  To provide information about your device app to AppMgr, you will need to invoke AppMgr with an AppMgr INI file, which contains app information such as where the CAB files are located.  Wit
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the AppMgr INI file and the location of the CAB files, AppMgr can be used by the end-user to install and remove the app to and from the device.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.2.\tab What is an AppMgr INI file?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 An AppMgr INI file is a text file containing information about your applica\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 tion, such as description text, display icon, and uninstall information.  A required piece of information is a list of }{
\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB files that contain your device app.  The AppMgr INI file is used as input into AppMgr, to provide it knowledge of
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  your installed app.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.3.\tab How do I call AppMgr?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 End-users can invoke AppMgr through ActiveSync (from the tools menu).  The application creator needs to invoke AppMgr with an AppMgr INI file, to provide information about the creator's device application.
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0   The important thing to note is to call AppMgr with a double-quoted absolute path to the AppMgr INI file.  The full path of AppMgr can be found from the desktop registry - it is stored in the default registry value of "HKLM\\
Software\\Microsoft\\CurrentVers\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 on\\App Paths\\CEAPPMGR.EXE".
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.4.\tab Where can I find the location of AppMgr on the user's desktop machine?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The full path of AppMgr can be found from the desktop registry - it is stored in the default registry value of "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\CurrentVersio\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\\App Paths\\CEAPPMGR.EXE".
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.5.\tab How do I create a single setup program to support both v1 and v2 devices?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 v1 devices still requires the use of PPCLoad to install the application to the device, while v2 (and future) devices will use the Application Insta\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
llation mechanism.  You can create a single setup program to support both v1 and v2 devices using the following pseudocode:
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 // early in setup, determine the installation method
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 if "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\App Paths\\CEAppMgr.EXE" reg\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 istry key exists then
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 use v2 AppInstall
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 else if "HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Pegasus\\InstalledDir" registry value exists then
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 use v1 PPCLoad
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 else
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 neither HPC Explorer nor ActiveSync is installed - exit setup
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 endif
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ...
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 // late in setup, copy the files and install to device
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 if using v2 AppInstall then
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 copy .CAB and .INI files to desktop PC
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 launch CEAppMgr with full file/path to the .INI file
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 else
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 copy application's SH3 and MIPS binaries and .LOAD file to desktop PC
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 as\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 k user to connect their device
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 get the connected-device processor type (from "HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Pegasus\\CPU" registry value)
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 call PPCLoad::Load_Init()
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 call PPCLoad::Load() with the CPU information, full file/path of the .LOAD file, etc.
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 call PPCL\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 oad::Exit()
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 endif
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.6.\tab Where does AppMgr get the full application name from?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 AppMgr will get your full application name from the CAB file itself.  It will concatenate the "Provider" and "AppName" values from the CabWiz INF file to create the full applic\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ation name.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.7.\tab Things to check for when encountering errors with AppMgr
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Use a double-quoted absolute path for the AppMgr INI file(s) parameter
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Use the "/report" parameter in debug versions to verify that AppMgr is using the correct information for\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the CAB files.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string list in the "CabFiles" key contains no unnecessary spaces.  Example:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1800\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Invalid:\tab CabFiles=app.sh3.cab,  app.mips.cab
\par \tab \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Valid:\tab CabFiles=app.sh3.cab,app.mips.cab
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string list in the "CabFiles" key matches the actual CAB files name and relative path.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Verify in the AppMgr INI file that the string value in the "Component" key exists elsewhere in the INI file.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - Verify that the\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  desktop setup program is calling the correct AppMgr INI file, using a full pathname.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - There are various third-party desktop setup programs that will not correctly update the actual file sizes when overwriting existing files.  Since AppMgr will verify the\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 actual file size with the embedded file size of the CAB file, make sure that the installed CAB file sizes are correct.  To ensure this happens for future upgrade scenarios, you can delete the known, existing CAB files on a reinstallation scenario.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx450\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\insrsid15337791 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.  W\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 CELoad
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.1.\tab What does WCELoad do?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 WCELoad is the }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  device tool that unpacks a given }{\fs20\insrsid7233056 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Pocket PC}{
\fs20\insrsid15337791 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  CAB file to install the application on the device.  The CAB extension is associated with WCELoad, so the end-user\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 can double-click on a CAB file to start the device installation.  Also, AppMgr launches WCELoad when it downloads the CAB files from the desktop to the device.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.2.\tab How do I call WCELoad?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Both the application creator and the end-user will not need to i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nvoke WCELoad directly.  The application creator will indirectly invoke WCELoad when AppMgr is called with an AppMgr INI file.  The end-user will indirectly invoke WCELoad when they double-click on a CAB file (that they may have downloaded from a website)
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 .
\par 
\par }}